  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has several key stages of development:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Initially emerged in response to organized crime activities in the early 20th century\n- Prohibition era in the United States saw initial attempts to criminalize proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970)\n- First comprehensive U.S. legislation targeting financial transactions\n- Required banks to report large cash transactions\n- Established framework for tracking potential illicit financial activities\n\n3. International Development\n- 1980s saw increased international cooperation against money laundering\n- United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs (1988)\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n\n4. Major Expansion with Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Laws\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Bank Secrecy Act amendments\n- Comprehensive regulations requiring financial institutions to implement robust reporting mechanisms\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded legal framework to include terrorism financing\n- Increased international information sharing and regulatory oversight\n\n6. Ongoing Global Refinement\n- Continuous updates to legal frameworks\n- Increasing complexity of financial technologies\n- Growing emphasis on cryptocurrency and digital transaction monitoring\n\nThis progression represents an evolving legal response to sophisticated financial criminal activities.",
